b'Meet Emmitt. Emmitt is a Southwest super-fan, and like many of us, had been missing the joy of traveling on his favorite airline. While staying at home for three-plus months, he asked mom @kendrajdrawing every day: "When are we going on Southwest Airlines?" Mom tried to keep him at bay with various aviation-related crafts, like painting some of his wooden model planes in Southwest colors. Emmit continued to dream of flying, drawing countless pictures of Southwest jets while he stayed at home. Finally, Emmitt\'s patience was rewarded. Although mom was anxious about flying in the current state, the Southwest staff put her and her family at ease, and her little aviators seemed to brighten everyone else\'s day too. And of course, Emmitt brought his model airplane onboard, leaving the entire Crew very impressed! Thanks for all the love, Emmitt. Sending our love right back at ya.'
b'Double tap when you see the plane taking off! This long exposure shot by @me_and_hou is simply *chef\xe2\x80\x99s kiss*.'

b'When @cassandrasotos boarded her flight from Nashville to Pittsburgh, she was surprised when a Southwest Crewmember asked her about the fiddle she had brought onboard. She was even more surprised when he asked her if she\'d want to play together, as he had brought his guitar on the flight. Without hesitation, she said yes! The ensuing jam session not only brought a smile to her face, but to the faces of her fellow Passengers as well. "This was my first time playing in flight and, especially after not being able to play live music for what feels like a million years, a wonderful reminder that music makes people SO happy for SO MANY reasons," Cassandra said. "I\'m so grateful to Zach for giving me this wonderful experience and to Southwest Airlines for cultivating such an amazing culture for their employees and passengers, especially musicians."'

b'When JacqueRae saw that a Passenger onboard was reading a book she was interested in, she approached him to discuss it. The book was about race, and the ensuing conversation was about the same topic. After an emotional and thoughtful conversation, it was time for JacqueRae to prepare for landing. As the Passengers were de-boarding the man she spoke with handed her a handwritten note, thanking her for the insightful and meaningful talk. The Passenger was Doug Parker, CEO of American Airlines. JacqueRae was shocked when she realized who she was speaking to, and immensely grateful for his openness and willingness to listen. "I want to work on a solution. I want to have conversations. This experience gives me hope. I feel like a shift will come out of this." We\xe2\x80\x99re so proud of Employees like JacqueRae, who truly embody what it means to have a #SouthwestHeart. We\xe2\x80\x99re committed to more conversations, more understanding, more change. It\xe2\x80\x99s the only way forward.'

b'We stand alongside our Black Employees, Customers, and communities whose voices will no longer be silenced. We must not tolerate racial injustice; we must not tolerate hate. We must stand for love.'

b'Before the #coronavirus pandemic, Bobby and Jenny, a husband and wife Flight Attendant duo, surprised first-time parents Dustin and Caren with an onboard baby shower. But Bobby and Jenny didn\xe2\x80\x99t know the Customers\xe2\x80\x99 inspiring story to become parents. Tune in to the @kellyclarksonshow on NBC this Monday, June 1, to hear their moving story of hope and love. Check your local listings for showtimes. #SouthwestHeartStrong #kellyclarksonshow'

b'Dorby F., a Customer Service Agent in Houston, has a son who graduated high school this spring. "Watching him work so hard all these years and not get to celebrate his achievements was heartbreaking. I knew other parents felt the same way!" Dorby worked with a group of Southwest Employees in HOU to throw their graduating seniors a special ceremony in the terminal. They worked with the city to coordinate the social distancing and headcount guidelines, and pulled together a special moment for their kids. "Seeing the smiles on the kids and parents\' faces was an amazing feeling." To all 2020 graduates, congratulations!'

b'When a group of Dallas-area students needed help transporting a donation of more than 110,000 medical-grade masks from New York to Dallas, they asked Southwest Cargo for help. We are proud to support these students in their quest to give back to their community. #SouthwestHeartStrong (:camera_with_flash:: @kellercam)'

Employees at our Ontario International Airport (ONT) and McCarran International Airport (LAS) Stations shared their love and appreciation for our nation\xe2\x80\x99s military, healthcare workers, and first responders by hand-writing hundreds of thank you notes. #SouthwestHeartStrong (:camera: Yvonne M. and Gareth R.)'

b'We\xe2\x80\x99re used to donating flights to help organizations in need. But now that the world is staying home, we saw a new opportunity to lend a hand. This week, we donated $400,000 worth of snacks and beverages from our Provisioning supplies. The drinks and snacks filled up 13 tractor trailers and were given to 15 local food banks and nearly 50 community organizations across the country. The world may be changing, but our Heart is not. #SouthwestHeartStrong #HeartInAction (:camera_with_flash: @kellercam)'
b'We\xe2\x80\x99ve introduced a foundational new cleaning method, with your Safety in mind. #SouthwestHeartStrong'

b'Meet Leonis. Leonis is a Customer Service Agent at Portland International Airport (PDX), where he was working like usual until he overheard a conversation between a Customer and a fellow Coheart nearby. Leonis learned the Customer\xe2\x80\x99s mother was recently hospitalized with COVID-19, and he was trying to book a last-minute flight to get to her. As Leonis listened, it became clear that the Customer needed help to cover the cost of the flight. That\xe2\x80\x99s when Leonis decided to go far beyond his usual duties and help. Using his Rapid Rewards Points, he volunteered to cover the cost of the Customer\xe2\x80\x99s travel\xe2\x80\x94an offer the Customer graciously accepted. Leonis, thank you for going above and beyond in exemplifying your Servant\xe2\x80\x99s Heart. #SouthwestHeartStrong (:camera_with_flash: @pdxairport)'
b'We\xe2\x80\x99ll always have our Heart. #SouthwestHeartStrong (:camera:: @jakesonaplane)'

b'Sometimes the smallest things make the biggest difference. Crew Members flying into Raleigh-Durham (RDU) in the past few days were greeted by a custom lunch bag from their Cohearts at the Station. Our Employees at RDU wanted to make sure the arriving Crew had a tasty meal, as more airport concession stands and local restaurants closed. Being part of the Southwest Family means going the extra mile to take care of each other, whether that means a friendly smile, an encouraging note, or a tasty PB&J! #SouthwestHeartStrong (:camera: Jay H. and Eddie V.)'

b'Our Teams have worked around the clock to adapt to our new landscape and to adjust our procedures and policies to take care of our Customers. Today our Chairman and CEO Gary Kelly announced changes to Tier Status and Companion Pass Benefits as well as our Travel Funds policy. We hope these policy changes bring you more comfort and confidence that we will be here, ready to serve you, when you\xe2\x80\x99re ready to travel. Click the link in our bio to read more about these recent policy changes. #SouthwestHeartStrong (photo by @kellercam)'

b'We\xe2\x80\x99re used to transporting you to what\xe2\x80\x99s important in your life, but these days, we\xe2\x80\x99re also committed to transporting what\xe2\x80\x99s important to you. These COVID-19 test kits being loaded up in Raleigh-Durham are the perfect example of how we\xe2\x80\x99re still committed to serving you. (photo by Matt M.)'

b'If you\xe2\x80\x99re flying into Denver during the holiday season, you might be able to spot this on the roof of a nearby home. The roof, and #SouthwestHeart light display, belong to Flight Attendant Oliver S. They\xe2\x80\x99re his way of spreading cheer to inbound Passengers during the winter months. Recently, Oliver decided it was time to spread some cheer again, regardless of the season. He said, \xe2\x80\x9cOur Southwest logo is more than a heart. It symbolizes the loyalty, passion, and protection that we bring as a team to get through the hardest of moments. This is for everyone at Southwest that has made our heart shine brighter than ever before, and for all our Customers who know that we will always protect them.\xe2\x80\x9d #SouthwestHeartStrong'
b'The world may be changing, but we\xe2\x80\x99re staying #SouthwestHeartStrong for you.'

b'This photo speaks volumes about the current state of our business. Like the flight in this photo taken by Robert, one of our Flight Attendants, many of our flights are carrying fewer Passengers than usual. But what you can\xe2\x80\x99t see in the picture is that the sole Customer onboard was a pulmonary critical care doctor. He was traveling to the west coast to volunteer with coronavirus relief. \nTo the people performing essential work, thank you. You\xe2\x80\x99re the reason we still fly. #SouthwestHeart'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cWe needed something positive to drown out the negative.\xe2\x80\x9d The desire to go above and beyond is an intrinsic part of being a Southwest Employee. In response to that feeling, many Employees in several of our stations have stepped up in the last week to start making masks for local hospitals and nursing homes. Donating their time, their machines, their skills, their fabric, all while keeping a safe distance from one another. \xe2\x80\x9cSince we can\xe2\x80\x99t give hugs, we\xe2\x80\x99re all giving each other an \xe2\x80\x98air\xe2\x80\x99 pat on the back, one we desperately needed,\xe2\x80\x9d said Kimberly in Kansas City. Sometimes the #SouthwestHeart is about more than air travel, it\xe2\x80\x99s about caring for others, and doing whatever you possibly can do to help.'

b'While so many of us continue to feel the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic, no one knows what is happening quite like our medical professionals. These brave souls soldier on in the midst of tremendous risk and exposure, constantly putting the needs of others above their own. Their selfless sacrifice is a beacon of light during such a dark time in our world, and no amount of gratitude and praise would ever be enough. Because of their courage, our family, our friends, our coworkers, our neighbors, and more have a fighting chance. More than a dozen healthcare professionals from Atlanta answered the call this past Friday evening to serve in New York. This photo embodies it all: bravery, courage, and sacrifice. If it were easy, everyone would do it, but we know that is not the case. Thankfully, this group and countless others do it each day, and for that we are forever grateful and in their debt. So to all the first responders, medical professionals, healthcare workers, and anyone else on the front lines today and every day to keep us safe, thank you. #SouthwestHeart (:camera_with_flash: Southwest Employee Dayartra E.)'

b'This photo was captured a couple of days ago during a thunderstorm at @dallaslovefield. It\xe2\x80\x99s a fitting representation of what\xe2\x80\x99s happening around the world right now and a reminder that beauty can exist amid a storm. The truth of the matter is that these are trying times for us all. The way we do business, interact with one another, and experience life has been affected. We have all been asked to adjust our daily lives, and while none of us know when it will end, we rise to the occasion. And for now, this is our new normal. However, we are not without hope because the human spirit and will to triumph over adversity will help guide us to brighter days. Even though there is a lot of uncertainty in the world, we take solace in the fact that this too shall pass. Until the rain lets up, take care of yourself, be kind to one another and remember we are always stronger together. (:camera_with_flash: DAL Airport Operations Officer @tonydhrt)'

b'Last month, Sadie was diagnosed with leukemia. Today is Sadie\xe2\x80\x99s birthday, and because of her ongoing treatment, she has to remain at home. Sadie\xe2\x80\x99s dad Travis, an Aircraft Dispatcher at Southwest, reached out to his fellow co-workers and asked if they could show their #SouthwestHeart and send Sadie some birthday love via mail. As of today, she has received over 400 packages and letters. If today is a day all about love, this is the kind of love we want to be spreading. Join us in wishing Sadie a happy birthday!'

b'Southwest has always been a huge part of Nick and Emily\xe2\x80\x99s long-distance love. But as much as they loved flying back and forth to see each other, Nick decided it was time to make things official. Earlier this year, he reached out to us on social media with a hopeful request: Could we help him plan the surprise of a lifetime? He wanted to make sure that he and Emily would be flying together forever. Emily had an upcoming flight from Chicago to Cincinnati (where Nick lived), and she was scheduled to fly alone. This was the perfect opportunity to take her completely by surprise! Nick worked with our Social Care Team to iron out the details with the Employees in Chicago, and then flew to Chicago himself, without Emily\xe2\x80\x99s knowledge. Right before her flight departed, Nick boarded the flight, got down on one knee, and popped the most important question of his life. She said yes! Congratulations to Emily and Nick, we are wishing you a lifetime of love! (@emilybrooke_257 @nboucher424)'

b'This is Sadie! She just turned three years old and she loves flying Southwest. When she was one year old, she was diagnosed with triplegia cerebral palsy, and recently had a life-changing surgery. Here\xe2\x80\x99s what mom told us Sadie has to say: \xe2\x80\x9cTraveling in general can be stressful for my parents because we have lots of extra things I need with me at all times. Southwest makes it easy by making sure I can preboard giving me extra time to get settled in my seat.  We love Southwest!\xe2\x80\x9d Well, we love YOU, Sadie! (@sadiegrace_xo)'
b'Saturday soaring. :smiling_face_with_heart-eyes:'

b'Twenty five years ago, Kyle gave a rose to everyone on his Southwest flight. You see, his girlfriend Staci was waiting for him unsuspectingly in the gate, and he had a special surprise planned. He handed out the roses as they de-boarded, and asked his fellow Passengers to each hand Staci their rose as they exited the jetbridge. Kyle was the final Passenger to come off the flight, and as he handed Staci the last rose, he dropped down to a knee and asked her to be his wife. She said \xe2\x80\x9cyes\xe2\x80\x9d 25 years ago. And today, when Kyle decided to surprise her and recreate that memorable moment, she said \xe2\x80\x9cyes\xe2\x80\x9d all over again. :rose:'

b'Last month, Grayson\xe2\x80\x99s mom reached out to us via social media with a hopeful plea: Help find her son\xe2\x80\x99s teddy bear, which had been left behind during a recent trip. Our Social Care Team immediately went into action, calling every possible location to speak with every possible person to try to hunt down Grayson\xe2\x80\x99s special teddy bear. Unfortunately, his teddy was nowhere to be found. After breaking the unfortunate news to her, the Social Care Team had an idea. If we couldn\xe2\x80\x99t find the original bear, would Grayson be happy to receive a new one? Mom thought he might like that. And he did! Swipe to see the introduction story our Social Care Team put together to send along with the new bear, which Grayson has already named, \xe2\x80\x9cJack.\xe2\x80\x9d We can\xe2\x80\x99t promise that we\xe2\x80\x99ll always be able to fix it, but we can promise we\xe2\x80\x99ll always try to make it right.'
